04827nam a22006855i 9780674735835DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013946873  a(OCoLC)1029833888  a(OCoLC)1032693028  a(OCoLC)1037980435  a(OCoLC)1042028266  a(OCoLC)1046605255  a(OCoLC)1047000574  a(OCoLC)979575092  a97806747358357 a10.4159/harvard.97806747358352doi  a(DE-B1597)427398  a(OCoLC)897600537  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHN90.C6bI44 2015eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a307.1/409732231 aImmerwahr, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThinking Small :bThe United States and the Lure of Community Development /cDaniel Immerwahr. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b14 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Modernization, Development, and Community -- tIntroduction: Actually Existing Localism -- t1. When Small Was Big -- t2. Development without Modernization -- t3. Peasantville -- t4. Grassroots Empire -- tEpilogue: What Is Dead and What Is Undead in Community Development? -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThinking Small tells the story of how the United States sought to rescue the world from poverty through small-scale, community-based approaches. And it also sounds a warning: such strategies, now again in vogue, have been tried before, with often disastrous consequences. It is common for historians to interpret the United States’ postwar development campaigns as ill-advised attempts to impose modernity upon poorer nations. The small-scale projects that are popular today mark a retreat from that top-down, heavy-handed approach. But Daniel Immerwahr shows that community-based development is nothing new: it has been present since the origins of international development practice, existing alongside—and sometimes at the heart of—grander schemes to modernize the global South. His transnational study follows a set of strange bedfellows—the Peace Corps and the CIA, Mohandas Gandhi and Ferdinand Marcos, antipoverty activists and Cold Warriors—united by their conviction that development should not be about engineers building dams but about communities shaping their own fates. The programs they designed covered hundreds of millions of people in some sixty countries, eventually making their way back to the United States itself during the War on Poverty. Yet the hope that small communities might lift themselves up was often disappointed, as self-help gave way to crushing forms of local oppression. Thinking Small challenges those who hope to eradicate poverty to think twice about the risks as well as the benefits of community development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommunity developmentzDeveloping countriesxHistory. 0aCommunity developmentzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEconomic assistance, AmericanzDeveloping countriesxHistory. 0aRural development projectszDeveloping countriesxHistory. 0aRural development projectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2015z9783110438635oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473583540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674735835423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674735835.jpg  a978-